&lt;p&gt;&lt;div style=&#34;border: 1px solid #DDDDDD; padding-left: 16px; padding-right: 16px;&#34;&gt;
&lt;h3 id=&#34;dcpu-16-toolkit:08e0386ce22622b66038f29292f02cb1&#34;&gt;DCPU-16 Toolkit&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The DCPU-16 Toolkit consists of an assembler, disassembler, and an emulator.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;what-is-a-dcpu-16:08e0386ce22622b66038f29292f02cb1&#34;&gt;What is a DCPU-16?&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The DCPU-16 is a fictional 16 bit processor created for the game 0x10c.  The DCPU-16 has 16 bit words, 0x10000 words of RAM, 8 registers, and runs at 100kHz.  The full spec is available &lt;a href=&#34;#&#34;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;.  There are several hardware devices designed for the DCPU-16, including a monitor, keyboard, and clock.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;emulator:08e0386ce22622b66038f29292f02cb1&#34;&gt;Emulator&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The emulator is a Windows console application written in C.  The emulator fully implements the DCPU-16 1.7 spec along with the LEM1802 monitor, generic keyboard, and generic clock.    With the emulator you can configure what hardware is attached the DCPU, load a binary to execute, and start and stop emulation.  Each monitor connected to the DCPU is displayed in a seperate window.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://andrewkersten.bitbucket.org/images/emulator_ui.png&#34; alt=&#34;DCPU-16 Emulator UI&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id=&#34;assembler-and-disassembler:08e0386ce22622b66038f29292f02cb1&#34;&gt;Assembler and Disassembler&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The assembler takes a DCPU-16 assembly source file as input and outputs a binary file that is executable by the emulator.  The assembler recognizes all 36 opcodes of the 1.7 spec as well as comments, labels, and the DAT directive.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The disassembler goes the other way, taking a binary file as input and outputing an assembly source file.&lt;/p&gt;

